  <a href="#1" id="1">
   To the rest of the world, he was known as Emperor Hirohito,
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   but in Japan his name was rarely used.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Japanese found the foreign practice
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   of using his given name impolite and referred to him simply as His majesty, the Emperor.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Japanese histories will record him as Emperor Showa, the name
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   he chose when he became emperor in 1926.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   His son, Akihito succeeded Emperor Hirohito and has chosen the name Heisei.
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   Japan numbers the years according to the emperor's tenure on the thrown.
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   Thus the first year of Hirohito's reign was Showa 1.
  </a>
  <a href="#10" id="10">
   Until he died,
  </a>
  <a href="#11" id="11">
   1989 was Showa 64,
  </a>
  <a href="#12" id="12">
   now it is Heisei 1.
